gaz_place_02.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 78.46\n|area_land_km2            = 20.44\n|area_water_km2           = 58.01\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 30.29\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 7.89\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 22.40\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"Census2010\">{{cite web|title=2010 City Population and Housing Occupancy Status|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 976\n|population_density_km2   = 55.76\n|population_density_sq_mi = 144.41\n|timezone                 = [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska (AKST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -9\n|timezone_DST             = AKDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -8\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 12\n|elevation_ft             = 39\n|coordinates              = {{coord|55|20|12|N|160|29|36|W|region:US-AK|display=inline}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 99661\n|area_code                = [[Area code 907|907]]\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n|GNIS_id                  = 1419182\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 02-67020\n|blank1_name              = \n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = [http://www.sandpointak.com/ sandpointak.com]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 1140\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n}}\n\n'''Sand Point''', also known as '''Popof Island''', is a city in [[Aleutians East Borough, Alaska]], United States. At the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] the population was 976, up from 952 in 2000. It is on northwestern [[Popof Island]], one of the [[Shumagin Islands]], off the [[Alaska Peninsula]]. It is the [[County seat|borough seat]] of Aleutians East Borough, and is near the entrance to the [[Bering Sea]].\n\nThe Aleutians East Borough School District is in Southwestern Alaska along the Alaska Peninsula and Aleutian Chain The District was formed in 1988 from smaller districts that consolidated and formed a Borough with taxing authority. The Borough and District boundaries are the same, and stretch over approximately {{convert|15000|sqmi|km2|sigfig=2}} of roadless, mostly treeless tundra, from the middle of the Alaska Peninsula to the north and east, going southwest out to Akutan just east of [[Dutch Harbor]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Fishing village of Sand Point, Popof Island, Alaska, nd (COBB 146).jpeg|thumb|Undated photograph of Sand Point by [[John Nathan Cobb]] (died 1930)]]\nSand Point was founded by a San Francisco fishing company in 1898 as a cod fishing station and trading post. [[Aleut people|Aleut]]s and Scandinavians were among the early residents. Gold mining was briefly a part of the economy during the early 1900s. Fishing remains an important industry, as Sand Point is home to one of the largest fishing fleets in the Aleutian Chain.\n\n==Description==\nAlmost half the inhabitants are of [[Aleut people|Aleut]] descent - mainly from the Qagan Tayagungin tribe, and support themselves by fishing and [[fish processing]]. There is a cold storage and fish-processing plant owned and operated by Trident Seafoods and Peter Pan has a support facility. There is an airport with a {{convert|5200|ft|m|sigfig=2}} paved runway and daily flights (weather permitting) to [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], {{convert|575|nmi|km|sigfig=2}} to the northeast.\n\nThe town is above the [[treeline]], and there is a small herd of 120 [[bison]] (first introduced in the 1930s) which provides some meat for the island's inhabitants. It is notorious for the high winds caused by the meeting of cold air flows from the [[Bering Sea]] with the warm air over the [[Japan Current]]. It has a [[maritime climate]], with temperature averages ranging from {{convert|\u22129|to|76|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}, an average snowfall of {{convert|52|in|cm}} and an average rainfall of {{convert|33|in|cm}}.\n\nThe [[Russian Orthodox]] St. Nicholas Chapel was built in Sand Point in 1933.<ref name=\"communitydb\">[http://www.commerce.state.ak.us/dca/commdb/CIS.cfm?Comm_Boro_name=Sand%20Point \"Alaska Community Database, Community Information Summaries - Sand Point\"]. Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs. Retrieved January 22, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 16\n|1920= 60\n|1930= 69\n|1940= 99\n|1950= 107\n|1960= 254\n|1970= 360\n|1980= 625\n|1990= 878\n|2000= 952\n|2010= 976\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=1140\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nSand Point first appeared on the 1890 U.S. Census as the Sand Point Station under Popof Island, but did not report a separate figure (the total population for the island and docked ships was 146). It first reported a separate figure in 1900 as Sand Point. It did not appear on the 1910 census, but returned in 1920 and in every successive census. It formally incorporated in 1966 and with the formation of the Aleutians East Borough in 1987, became the seat of government.\n\nAs of the census<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 952 people, 229 households, and 155 families residing in the city. The population density was 122.1 people per square mile (47.1/km\u00b2). There were 282 housing units at an average density of 36.2 per square&nbsp;mile (14.0/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 27.73% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 1.47% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 42.33% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 23.21% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.32% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 2.21% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.73% from two or more races. 13.55% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 229 households out of which 39.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.4% were married couples living together, 15.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 31.9% were non-families. 25.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 3.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.67 and the average family size was 3.17.\n\nIn the city, the age distribution of the population shows 20.4% under the age of 18, 8.6% from 18 to 24, 41.5% from 25 to 44, 26.3% from 45 to 64, and 3.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 165.2 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 181.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $55,417, and the median income for a family was $58,000. Males had a median income of $20,000 versus $22,500 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $21,954. About 10.3% of families and 16.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 14.4% of those under age 18 and 32.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Climate==\nLike all of [[Southwest Alaska]], Sand Point has a [[subpolar oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Cfc''), though compared to most parts of the region it is a little less rainy and has fewer wet days - 145 as compared to over 220 throughout the Aleutian Islands and in most of [[Southeast Alaska]].\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Sand Point, Alaska\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 48\n|Feb record high F = 56\n|Mar record high F = 46\n|Apr record high F = 52\n|May record high F = 59\n|Jun record high F = 65\n|Jul record high F = 71\n|Aug record high F = 72\n|Sep record high F = 64\n|Oct record high F = 57\n|Nov record high F = 52\n|Dec record high F = 48\n|year record high F =72\n|Jan high F = 36.2\n|Feb high F = 34.9\n|Mar high F = 37.7\n|Apr high F = 39.2\n|May high F = 45.3\n|Jun high F = 51.9\n|Jul high F = 57.5\n|Aug high F = 57.6\n|Sep high F = 53.9\n|Oct high F = 46.6\n|Nov high F = 41.3\n|Dec high F = 38.6\n|year high F =45.1\n|Jan low F = 29.0\n|Feb low F = 27.0\n|Mar low F = 28.9\n|Apr low F = 30.6\n|May low F = 36.4\n|Jun low F = 41.8\n|Jul low F = 46.8\n|Aug low F = 48.1\n|Sep low F = 44.1\n|Oct low F = 37.6\n|Nov low F = 33.2\n|Dec low F = 31.3\n|year low F =36.2\n|Jan record low F = \u221212\n|Feb record low F =   3\n|Mar record low F =   6\n|Apr record low F =   8\n|May record low F =  12\n|Jun record low F =  30\n|Jul record low F =  34\n|Aug record low F =  36\n|Sep record low F =  25\n|Oct record low F =  24\n|Nov record low F =  18\n|Dec record low F =  10\n|year record low F= \u221212\n|precipitation colour=green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 3.88\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.60\n|Mar precipitation inch = 3.26\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.41\n|May precipitation inch = 3.03\n|Jun precipitation inch = 3.15\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.87\n|Aug precipitation inch = 4.01\n|Sep precipitation inch = 6.32\n|Oct precipitation inch = 3.89\n|Nov precipitation inch = 3.47\n|Dec precipitation inch = 5.79\n|year precipitation inch=44.68\n|unit precipitation days = 0.01 inch\n|Jan precipitation days = 13\n|Feb precipitation days = 10\n|Mar precipitation days = 13\n|Apr precipitation days = 10\n|May precipitation days = 11\n|Jun precipitation days = 12\n|Jul precipitation days = 11\n|Aug precipitation days = 13\n|Sep precipitation days = 14\n|Oct precipitation days = 12\n|Nov precipitation days = 12\n|Dec precipitation days = 14\n\n|Jan snow inch = 5.6\n|Feb snow inch = 1.8\n|Mar snow inch = 1.5\n|Apr snow inch = 0.8\n|May snow inch = 0\n|Jun snow inch = 0\n|Jul snow inch = 0\n|Aug snow inch = 0\n|Sep snow inch = 0\n|Oct snow inch = 0\n|Nov snow inch = 1.2\n|Dec snow inch = 2.0\n|year snow inch=12.9\n|source 1 = <ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?aksand | title =SAND POINT, ALASKA - Period of Record Monthly Climate Summary 6/1/1980 to 6/30/1994 | accessdate =  December 21, 2009| publisher = Western Regional Climate Center}}</ref>\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n==Culture==\nSand Point is a mixed Native and non-Native community. More than 50% of the permanent residents in Sand Point are known as [[Aleut people|Aleut]]s or [[Unangan]]. Every July the town hosts a Culture Camp in which Aleut traditions such as dance, sewing Aleut dresses, playing drums, building kayaks, knot tying, and weaving are taught. Culture Camp has an Aleut language component built into the program.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|28.9|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|7.8|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|21.1|sqmi|km2}} of it (73.05%) is water.\n\n==Education==\nThere is one school, the Sand Point School, operated by the [[Aleutians East Borough School District]] (AEBSD).<ref>{{Cite web | title = District Schools | work = Aleutians East Borough School District | url = http://aebsdonline.org/mod/resource/view.php?id=146 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100526104657/http://aebsdonline.org/mod/resource/view.php?id=146 | archivedate = May 26, 2010 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are approximately one hundred students in the Sand Point School.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}{{when|date=February 2017}} In addition to classroom space, the school houses a library media center, gymnasium, weight room, indoor pool and shop. The Sand Point School is part of the Aleutians East Borough School District. The superintendent of the AEBSD{{when|date=February 2017}} is Dr. Doug Conboy and the principal of the Sand Point School is Ralph Lindquist.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Sand Point: Civic & Government| work = KSDP 830 AM \u2013 Sand Point, AK  | url = http://apradio.org/c/welcome-to-sand-point/civic-government/| accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> Circa 1978 the school, then a part of the [[Aleutian Region School District]], had a 13 teachers,<ref name=Aleutp58>''Aleutian Islands, Aleutian Peninsula Debris Removal: Environmental Impact Statement''. [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]], 1980. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=UvoyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA58 58].</ref> and 136 students.<ref name=Aleutp59>''Aleutian Islands, Aleutian Peninsula Debris Removal: Environmental Impact Statement''. [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]], 1980. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=UvoyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA59 59].</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Peninsula Airways]] (PenAir) offers daily but expensive flights from Anchorage to Sand Point. Often it is difficult to obtain a plane ticket off of the island with costs occasionally reaching $1200 for a round-trip ticket.\n\nCargo service to Sand Point is available on PenAir and [[Alaska Central Express]] (ACE) Air Cargo.  PenAir has cargo flights to Sand Point six mornings a week.  ACE Air Cargo flies to Sand Point several days a week.  \n[http://www.coastaltransportation.com/ ''Coastal Transportation''] is a Seattle-based marine carrier that provides weekly year-around service to communities throughout the Aleutians, including Sand Point.\n\nDuring the summer and into the fall, the Alaska Marine Highway operates the [[MV Tustumena|Tustumena]]. The Tustumena stops in Sand Point four times per month. From Sand Point the ferry goes to King Cove, Cold Bay, False Pass and Dutch Harbor. The ship has staterooms and dining room service. The ferry takes cars and trucks. As of 2017 ferry delays have been common.\n\nIn Sand Point, rental cars are available from the Harbor Cafe and the Marine View Bed & Breakfast.\n\n==Wind Power==\nIn 2012, two .5MW wind turbines were installed with blade diameters of 19.5 meters and a height of 59.5 meters.\n\n==Activities==\nMany people enjoy hunting for [[rock ptarmigan|ptarmigan]] and [[American bison|buffalo]].  [[Commercial fishing|Commercial]] and [[Recreational fishing|pole fishing]] are enjoyable pastimes for the residents of Sand Point. [[Boating]]  and riding [[all-terrain vehicle]]s (ATVs) are popular pastimes as well. There is an annual Silver Salmon Derby in which contestants try to catch the largest fish to earn a cash prize. Adults can play [[Bingo (U.S.)|Bingo]] and [[Pull-tab|pull tabs]] on Sunday. The [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys and Girls Club]] offers after-school activities.\nMany adults spend their time at the local tavern and lounge both owned and operated by the Shumagin Corporation. Due to the small community and the lack of entertainment, many newcomers find themselves leaving. This includes many of the teachers.\n\n==Fishing industry==\nLike most Aleutian communities, commercial fishing drives the local economy. The Aleutians' largest fishing fleet is based in Sand Point.<ref name=\"communitydb\" /> [[Trident Seafoods]] has a major [[Pacific cod]], [[pollock]], [[salmon]] and [[halibut]] [[Fish processing|processing plant]], and provides fuel and other services. Peter Pan Seafoods owns a storage and transfer facility. In 1991, New West Fisheries had a [[Factory ship|floating processor]] near the city dock for [[Pacific cod]] processing. Residents in Sand Point have to acquire commercial fishing permits to participate in the fisheries.\n\nThe city completed a major rehabilitation of the Robert E. Galovin Small Boat Harbor in the summer of 2014. The harbor can hold more than 150 boats in permanent slips, as well as transient vessels. There is also a new boat harbor on the waterfront next to the small boat harbor and City dock. This harbor was built by the Borough and Army Corps of Engineers, but does not have any floats.\n\n==Business and shopping==\nThe AC Store ([[Alaska Commercial Company]]) provides groceries, apparel, motorized vehicles such as ATVs, and toiletries. Small local stores provide goods like hardware, toys, groceries, and electronics. There is a small selection of restaurants in the town. Alcohol can be purchased at two locations. A [[bed and breakfast]] is near the Trident bunkhouses. Cut R' Loose Coffee provides espresso and other specialty drinks to the local community.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Radio===\n* [[KSDP (AM)|KSDP]] 830 AM (Local NPR and APRN affiliate) (non-commercial community service)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Sand Point, Alaska}}\n\n{{Coord|display=title|55.336593|-160.493234}}\n{{Alaska borough seats}}\n{{Aleutians East Borough, Alaska}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Borough seats in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Aleutians East Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1898]]\n[[Category:Shumagin Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Lam-ang", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed GNIS ID", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sand_Point,_Alaska"}
{"title_page": "Duty Entitlement Pass Book", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2009}}\n'''DEPB (Duty Entitlement Pass Book )''' is an export incentive scheme of [[Government of India|Indian Government]] provided to Exporters in [[India]].<ref>[http://dgftcom.nic.in/exim/2000/procedures/bchap-04.html] Policy relating to the Duty Exemption/Remission Scheme is prescribed in Chapter 4 of the Policy-Sourrnment of India</ref>\n\nDuty Entitlement Pass Book Scheme (DEPB) is an export incentive scheme. The objective of DEPB is to neutralise the incidence of Customs duty on the import content of the export product. The neutralisation shall be provided by way of grant of duty credit against the export product. Under the DEPB, an exporter may apply for credit, as a specified percentage of FOB value of exports made in freely convertible currency.\n\nNotified on 1/4/1997, the DEPB Scheme consisted of (a) Post-export DEPB and (b) Pre-export DEPB. The pre-export DEPB scheme was abolished w.e.f. 1/4/2000. Under the post-export DEPB, which is issued after exports, the exporter is given a duty entitlement Pass Book Scheme at a pre-determined credit on the FOB value. The DEPB rates allows import of any items except the items which are otherwise restricted for [[imports]]. Items such as Gold Nibs, Gold Pen, Gold watches etc. though covered under the generic description of [[Writing implement|writing instruments]], components of writing instruments and watches are thus not eligible for benefit under the DEPB scheme.\n\nThe DEPB Rates are applied on the basis of FOB value or value cap whichever is lower. For example, if the FOB value is Rs.700/- per piece, and the value cap is Rs.500/- per piece, the DEPB rate shall be applied on Rs.500/-. The DEPB rate and the value cap shall be applicable as existing on the date of exports as defined in paragraph 15.15 of Handbook (Vol.1).\n\nDEPB Scheme is issued only on post-export basis and pre/export DEPB Scheme has been discontinued. The provisions of DEPB Scheme are mentioned in Para 4.3 and 4.3.1 to 4.3.5 of the [[International trade|Foreign Trade]] Policy or Exim Policy. One significant change in the new DEPB Scheme is that in terms of Para 4.3.5 of the Exim Policy even [[Excise|excise duty]] paid in cash on inputs used in the manufacture of export product shall be eligible for brand rate of [[duty drawback]] as per rules framed by Department of Revenue which was not mentioned in the earlier DEPB Scheme.\n\n==Benefits of DEPB Rates==\n\nThe benefit of DEPB schemes is available on the export products having extraneous material up to 8% by material up to 5% shall be ignored and the DEPB rate as notified for that export product is to be allowed.\n\n==Review of DEPB Rates==\n\nThe Government of India review<ref>[http://m.mydigitalfc.com/government-finance/depb-scheme-likely-be-extended-till-march-31-408] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120711235208/http://m.mydigitalfc.com/government-finance/depb-scheme-likely-be-extended-till-march-31-408 |date=2012-07-11 }} DEPB scheme likely to be extended till March 31-Source-Financial Chronicle</ref> the DEPB rates after getting the appropriate an export import data on [[FOB (shipping)]] value of [[exports]] and  [[Cost, Insurance and Freight]] (CIF) value of inputs used in the export product, as per SION. Such data and information is usually obtained from the concerned [[Export Promotion Council]]s.\n\n==Implementation of the DEPB Rates==\n\nSome additional facilities as listed below have been provided for better implementation of the DEPB Rates\n\n*DEPB rates rationalized to account for the changes in [[Customs|Customs duties]].\n*Caps fixed on certain items but there would be no verification of Present Market Value (PMV) on such items.\n*A number of [[port]]s have been added for availing facilities under the Duty Exemption Scheme, including DEPB.\n*The threshold limit of Rs. 200 million for fixing new DEPB rates removed.\n\n===Provisional DEPB Rate===\n\nThe main objective behind the provisional DEPB rates is to encourage [[Diversification (marketing strategy)|diversification]] and to promote export of new products. However, provisional DEPB rates would be valid for a limited period of time during which [[exporter]] would furnish data on [[export]] and [[import]] for regular fixation of rates.\n\n===Maintenance of Record===\n\nIt is necessary for  [[Custom house|Custom House]] at ports to maintain a separate [[Public records|record]] of details of exports made under DEPB Schemes.\n\n===Port of Registration===\n\nThe exports/imports made from the specified ports given shall be entitled for DEPB.\n\n* Sea Ports: [[Mumbai]], [[Kolkata]], [[Cochin]], [[Dahej]], [[Kakinada]], [[Kandla]], [[Mangalore]], [[Mormugao]], [[Mundra]], [[Chennai]], [[Nhava Sheva]], [[Paradeep]], [[Pipavav]], [[Sikka, India|Sikka]], [[Tuticorin]] [[Vishakhapatnam]], [[Surat]] (Magdalla), [[Nagapattinam]], [[Okha, Gujarat|Okha]], [[Dharamtar]] and [[Jamnagar]].\n* Airports: [[Ahmedabad]], [[Bangalore]], [[Bhubaneshwar]] [[Mumbai]], [[Kolkata]] [[Coimbatore]] [[Cargo airline|Air Cargo]] Complex, [[Cochin]], [[Delhi]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Jaipur]], [[Srinagar]], [[Trivandrum]], [[Varanasi]], [[Nagpur]] and [[Chennai]].\n* ICDs : [[Agra]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Bangalore]], [[Bhiwadi]], [[Coimbatore]], Daulatabad, (Wanjarwadi and Maliwada), [[Delhi]], Dighi ([[Pune]]), [[Faridabad]], [[Guntur]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Jaipur]], [[Jallandhar]], [[Jodhpur]], [[Kanpur]], [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]], [[Ludhiana]], [[Madurai]] and the land Customs station at Ranaghat Mallanpur, Moradabad, Meerut Nagpur, [[Nasik]], Gauhati (Amingaon), [[Pimpri]] (Pune), Pitampur (Indore), Rudrapur (Nainital), Salem Singanalur, Surat, Tirupur, Udaipur, Vadodara, Varanasi, Waluj, Bhilwara, Pondicherry, Garhi-Harsaru, Bhatinda, Dappar, Chheharata (Amritsar), Karur, Miraj and Rewari.\n* LCS: Ranaghat, Singhabad, Raxaul, Jogbani, Nautanva ( Sonauli), Petrapole and Mahadipur.\n\nThe exports made to the following [[Special Economic Zone]]s (SEZ) are also entitled to DEPB.\n\n* SEZ : [[Santacruz, Mumbai|Santacruz]], [[Kandla]], [[Kochi]], [[Vishakhapatnam]], [[Chennai]], FALTA, [[Surat]], [[NOIDA]]\n\n===Credit under DEPB and Present Market Value===\n\nIn respect of products where rate of credit entitlement under DEPB Scheme comes to 10% or more, amount of [[Credit (finance)|credit]] against each such export product shall not exceed 50% of Present Market Value (PMV) of export product. During export, exporter shall [[declare]] on shipping bill that benefit under DEPB Scheme would not exceed 50% of PMV of export product.\n\nHowever PMV declaration shall not be applicable for products for which value cap exists irrespective of DEPB rate of product.\n\n===Utilization of DEPB credit===\n\nCredit given under DEPB Schemes is utilized for payment of [[India]]n [[customs]] duty\n\n===Re-export of goods imported under DEPB Scheme===\n\nIn case of return of any exported goods, which has been found defective or unfit for use may be again exported according to the exim guidelines as mentioned by the [[Department of Revenue (India)|Department of Revenue]].\n\nIn such cases 98% of the credit amount debited against DEPB for the export of such goods is generated by the concerned Commissioner of  Customs in the form of a Certificate, containing the amount generated and the details of the original DEPB. On the basis of certificate, a fresh DEPB is issued by the concerned DGFT Regional Authority. It is important to note that the issued DEPB have the same port of registration and shall be valid for a period equivalent to the balance period available on the date of import of such defective/unfit [[good (economics)|good]]s.\n\n=== Closure of DEPB Scheme ===\nDEPB scheme has been withdrawn since October 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/DEPB-scheme-to-end-on-Oct-1/articleshow/10012831.cms|title=Time of India|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign trade of India]]\n[[Category:Custom and excise duties in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2009}}\n'''DEPB (Duty Entitlement Pass Book )''' is an export incentive scheme of [[Government of India|Indian Government]] provided to Exporters in [[India]].<ref>[http://dgftcom.nic.in/exim/2000/procedures/bchap-04.html] Policy relating to the Duty Exemption/Remission Scheme is prescribed in Chapter 4 of the Policy-Sourrnment of India</ref>\n\nDuty Entitlement Pass Book Scheme (DEPB) is an export incentive scheme. The objective of DEPB is to neutralise the incidence of Customs duty on the import content of the export product. The neutralisation shall be provided by way of grant of duty credit against the export product. Under the DEPB, an exporter may apply for credit, as a specified percentage of FOB value of exports made in freely convertible currency.\n\nNotified on 1/4/1997, the DEPB Scheme consisted of (a) Post-export DEPB and (b) Pre-export DEPB. The pre-export DEPB scheme was abolished w.e.f. 1/4/2000. Under the post-export DEPB, which is issued after exports, the exporter is given a duty entitlement Pass Book Scheme at a pre-determined credit on the FOB value. The DEPB rates allows import of any items except the items which are otherwise restricted for [[imports]]. Items such as Gold Nibs, Gold Pen, Gold watches etc. though covered under the generic description of [[Writing implement|writing instruments]], components of writing instruments and watches are thus not eligible for benefit under the DEPB scheme.\n\nThe DEPB Rates are applied on the basis of FOB value or value cap whichever is lower. For example, if the FOB value is Rs.700/- per piece, and the value cap is Rs.500/- per piece, the DEPB rate shall be applied on Rs.500/-. The DEPB rate and the value cap shall be applicable as existing on the date of exports as defined in paragraph 15.15 of Handbook (Vol.1).\n\nDEPB Scheme is issued only on post-export basis and pre/export DEPB Scheme has been discontinued. The provisions of DEPB Scheme are mentioned in Para 4.3 and 4.3.1 to 4.3.5 of the [[International trade|Foreign Trade]] Policy or Exim Policy. One significant change in the new DEPB Scheme is that in terms of Para 4.3.5 of the Exim Policy even [[Excise|excise duty]] paid in cash on inputs used in the manufacture of export product shall be eligible for brand rate of [[duty drawback]] as per rules framed by Department of Revenue which was not mentioned in the earlier DEPB Scheme.\n\n==Benefits of DEPB Rates==\n\nThe benefit of DEPB schemes is available on the export products having extraneous material up to 8% by material up to 5% shall be ignored and the DEPB rate as notified for that export product is to be allowed.\n\n==Review of DEPB Rates==\n\nThe Government of India review<ref>[http://m.mydigitalfc.com/government-finance/depb-scheme-likely-be-extended-till-march-31-408] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120711235208/http://m.mydigitalfc.com/government-finance/depb-scheme-likely-be-extended-till-march-31-408 |date=2012-07-11 }} DEPB scheme likely to be extended till March 31-Source-Financial Chronicle</ref> the DEPB rates after getting the appropriate an export import data on [[FOB (shipping)]] value of [[exports]] and  [[Cost, Insurance and Freight]] (CIF) value of inputs used in the export product, as per SION. Such data and information is usually obtained from the concerned [[Export Promotion Council]]s.\n\n==Implementation of the DEPB Rates==\n\nSome additional facilities as listed below have been provided for better implementation of the DEPB Rates\n\n*DEPB rates rationalized to account for the changes in [[Customs|Customs duties]].\n*Caps fixed on certain items but there would be no verification of Present Market Value (PMV) on such items.\n*A number of [[port]]s have been added for availing facilities under the Duty Exemption Scheme, including DEPB.\n*The threshold limit of Rs. 200 million for fixing new DEPB rates removed.\n\n===Provisional DEPB Rate===\n\nThe main objective behind the provisional DEPB rates is to encourage [[Diversification (marketing strategy)|diversification]] and to promote export of new products. However, provisional DEPB rates would be valid for a limited period of time during which [[exporter]] would furnish data on [[export]] and [[import]] for regular fixation of rates.\n\n===Maintenance of Record===\n\nIt is necessary for  [[Custom House]] at ports to maintain a separate [[Public records|record]] of details of exports made under DEPB Schemes.\n\n===Port of Registration===\n\nThe exports/imports made from the specified ports given shall be entitled for DEPB.\n\n* Sea Ports: [[Mumbai]], [[Kolkata]], [[Cochin]], [[Dahej]], [[Kakinada]], [[Kandla]], [[Mangalore]], [[Mormugao]], [[Mundra]], [[Chennai]], [[Nhava Sheva]], [[Paradeep]], [[Pipavav]], [[Sikka, India|Sikka]], [[Tuticorin]] [[Vishakhapatnam]], [[Surat]] (Magdalla), [[Nagapattinam]], [[Okha, Gujarat|Okha]], [[Dharamtar]] and [[Jamnagar]].\n* Airports: [[Ahmedabad]], [[Bangalore]], [[Bhubaneshwar]] [[Mumbai]], [[Kolkata]] [[Coimbatore]] [[Cargo airline|Air Cargo]] Complex, [[Cochin]], [[Delhi]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Jaipur]], [[Srinagar]], [[Trivandrum]], [[Varanasi]], [[Nagpur]] and [[Chennai]].\n* ICDs : [[Agra]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Bangalore]], [[Bhiwadi]], [[Coimbatore]], Daulatabad, (Wanjarwadi and Maliwada), [[Delhi]], Dighi ([[Pune]]), [[Faridabad]], [[Guntur]], [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Jaipur]], [[Jallandhar]], [[Jodhpur]], [[Kanpur]], [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]], [[Ludhiana]], [[Madurai]] and the land Customs station at Ranaghat Mallanpur, Moradabad, Meerut Nagpur, [[Nasik]], Gauhati (Amingaon), [[Pimpri]] (Pune), Pitampur (Indore), Rudrapur (Nainital), Salem Singanalur, Surat, Tirupur, Udaipur, Vadodara, Varanasi, Waluj, Bhilwara, Pondicherry, Garhi-Harsaru, Bhatinda, Dappar, Chheharata (Amritsar), Karur, Miraj and Rewari.\n* LCS: Ranaghat, Singhabad, Raxaul, Jogbani, Nautanva ( Sonauli), Petrapole and Mahadipur.\n\nThe exports made to the following [[Special Economic Zone]]s (SEZ) are also entitled to DEPB.\n\n* SEZ : [[Santacruz, Mumbai|Santacruz]], [[Kandla]], [[Kochi]], [[Vishakhapatnam]], [[Chennai]], FALTA, [[Surat]], [[NOIDA]]\n\n===Credit under DEPB and Present Market Value===\n\nIn respect of products where rate of credit entitlement under DEPB Scheme comes to 10% or more, amount of [[Credit (finance)|credit]] against each such export product shall not exceed 50% of Present Market Value (PMV) of export product. During export, exporter shall [[declare]] on shipping bill that benefit under DEPB Scheme would not exceed 50% of PMV of export product.\n\nHowever PMV declaration shall not be applicable for products for which value cap exists irrespective of DEPB rate of product.\n\n===Utilization of DEPB credit===\n\nCredit given under DEPB Schemes is utilized for payment of [[India]]n [[customs]] duty\n\n===Re-export of goods imported under DEPB Scheme===\n\nIn case of return of any exported goods, which has been found defective or unfit for use may be again exported according to the exim guidelines as mentioned by the [[Department of Revenue (India)|Department of Revenue]].\n\nIn such cases 98% of the credit amount debited against DEPB for the export of such goods is generated by the concerned Commissioner of  Customs in the form of a Certificate, containing the amount generated and the details of the original DEPB. On the basis of certificate, a fresh DEPB is issued by the concerned DGFT Regional Authority. It is important to note that the issued DEPB have the same port of registration and shall be valid for a period equivalent to the balance period available on the date of import of such defective/unfit [[good (economics)|good]]s.\n\n=== Closure of DEPB Scheme ===\nDEPB scheme has been withdrawn since October 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/DEPB-scheme-to-end-on-Oct-1/articleshow/10012831.cms|title=Time of India|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign trade of India]]\n[[Category:Custom and excise duties in India]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCustom House (disambiguation)(link changed toCustom house) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duty_Entitlement_Pass_Book"}
{"title_page": "Billy Unger", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Billy Unger\n| image        =\n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = William Brent Unger \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1995|10|15}}<ref name=medianet/>\n| birth_place  = [[Palm Beach County, Florida]], United States\n| other_names  = William Brent\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 2007\u2013present\n| known_for    = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Lab Rats (American TV series)|Lab Rats]]'' (2012\u20132016)\n* ''[[Lab Rats: Elite Force]]'' (2016)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''William Brent Unger''' (born October 15, 1995) is an American actor. He is known for playing Chase on the Disney XD series [[Lab Rats (U.S. TV series)|''Lab Rats'']] and ''[[Lab Rats: Elite Force]]''. Credited as '''Billy Unger''' before 2016, starting with ''Lab Rats: Elite Force'' he is credited as '''William Brent'''.<ref name=\"LR:EF-premiere\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2016/02/02/disney-xds-new-spinoff-series-lab-rats-elite-force-premieres-wednesday-march-2-239011/20160202disneyxd01/ |title=Disney XD's New Spinoff Series \"Lab Rats: Elite Force\" Premieres Wednesday, March 2 |publisher=[[Disney XD]] |date=February 2, 2016 |accessdate=February 2, 2016 |via=[[The Futon Critic]] |quote=Created and executive-produced by Chris Peterson and Bryan Moore (\"That '70s Show\"), the series stars Bradley Steven Perry as Kaz, William Brent (formerly known as Billy Unger) as Chase, Jake Short as Oliver, Paris Berelc as Skylar and Kelli Berglund as Bree.}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nUnger was born in [[Palm Beach County, Florida]]. He moved to Hollywood with his family in 2006.<ref name=\"medianet\" />\n\n==Career==\nSince moving to LA, Unger has guest starred on [[Disney XD]]'s ''[[Kickin' It]]'', [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[Sonny with a Chance]]'' and ''[[A.N.T. Farm]]'', and on ''[[No Ordinary Family]]'', ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'', ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|Hawthorne]]'', ''[[Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles]]'', ''[[Mental (TV series)|Mental]]'', ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Cold Case (TV series)|Cold Case]]'', and ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]''. He also made an appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]''.\n\nUnger has appeared in the films ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]'', ''[[You Again]]'', ''[[Monster Mutt (film)|Monster Mutt]]'', ''[[Opposite Day]]'', ''[[Jack and the Beanstalk (2010 film)|Jack and the Beanstalk]]'', and ''[[Rock Slyde]]''.\n\nBeginning in 2012 he began starring as Chase, the youngest of the super-human bionic teens, in the [[Disney XD]] series ''[[Lab Rats (U.S. TV series)|Lab Rats]]''. In 2016, he continued to play Chase on the ''Lab Rats'' [[Spin-off (media)|spinoff]] series ''[[Lab Rats: Elite Force]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/disney-xd-lab-rats-elite-force-spinoff-mighty-med-1201585323/ |title=Disney XD Greenlights \u2018Lab Rats\u2019 and \u2018Mighty Med\u2019 Spinoff Series |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 3, 2015 |accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/lab-rats-mighty-med-end-spinoff-series-disney-xd-1201513610/|title=Lab Rats & Mighty Med Spin-off Series to Succeed the Two Comedies on Disney XD|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=September 3, 2015|accessdate=September 3, 2015}}</ref> now credited as William Brent.<ref name=\"LR:EF-premiere\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Seven's Eleven: Sweet Toys'' || Frankie || \n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]'' || Charles Gates ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Rock Slyde]]'' || Young Rock Slyde ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Crank: High Voltage]]'' || Young [[Chev Chelios]] ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''