.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900092&type=unger |title=''Lab Rats'' Billy Unger \"Chase\" |publisher=Disney XD Medianet |year=2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69CXwLlsn?url=http://www.disneyxdmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900092&type=unger |archivedate=July 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2598945}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Unger, Billy}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Florida]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Beach County, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Haydenbug2015", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Unger"}
{"title_page": "Aron Ralston", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = \n| image = Aron Ralston on Capitol Peak Winter 2003.JPG\n| image_size = \n| alt = Aron Ralston standing in the snow on the top of Capitol Peak\n| caption = Ralston on Capitol Peak in winter 2003\n| birth_name = Aron Lee Ralston\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1975|10|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Marion, Ohio|Marion]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"birth\">Ohio Birth Index, 1908-2011</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Carnegie Mellon University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| occupation = [[Motivational speaker]], [[mountainee]], [[mechanical engineer]]\n| notable_works = ''[[Between a Rock and a Hard Place (book)|Between a Rock and a Hard Place]]''\n| residence = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Jessica Trusty|2009|2012|end=divorced}}\n| partner= Vita Shannon (2012&ndash;2013)\n| children = 2|\n}}\n'''Aron Lee Ralston''' (born October 27, 1975) is an [[United States|American]] [[outdoorsman]], [[mechanical engineer]] and [[motivational speaker]] known for surviving a [[canyoneering]] accident by cutting off his own arm. During a solo descent of [[Bluejohn Canyon]] in southeastern [[Utah]] he dislodged a boulder, pinning his right wrist to the side of the canyon wall. After five days he was able to amputate his arm with a dull pocketknife, make his way through the rest of the canyon, rappel down a {{convert|65|feet|m|adj=on}} drop, and hike {{convert|7|miles|km}} to safety.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/may/03/duncancampbell |title=Mountaineer trapped by boulder amputated arm with pocketknife|newspaper=The Guardian |author=Duncan Campbell |date=2003-05-03 |accessdate=2010-12-13 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=brhp>{{cite book|author=Aron Ralston|title=Between a Rock and a Hard Place |url=https://archive.org/details/betweenrockandha00rals|url-access=registration|isbn=0-7432-6354-5|publisher=Atria Books|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nThe incident is documented in Ralston's autobiography ''[[Between a Rock and a Hard Place (book)|Between a Rock and a Hard Place]]'' and is the subject of the 2010 film ''[[127 Hours]]'' where he is portrayed by [[James Franco]].\n\nAfter the accident he continued mountaineering and became the first person to ascend all of [[List of Colorado fourteeners|Colorado's fourteeners]] solo in winter.\n\n==Early life==\n\nAron Ralston was born on October 27, 1975 in [[Marion, Ohio]].<ref name=\"birth\"/> He and his family moved to [[Denver]] when he was 12, where he attended Cherry Creek High School and learned to ski and backpack. He received his college degree from [[Carnegie Mellon University]] in [[Pittsburgh]], finishing with degrees in mechanical engineering and [[French language|French]], with a minor in [[piano]].<ref name=brhp/> At Carnegie Mellon, he served as a resident assistant, studied abroad, and was an active [[intramural sports]] participant.<ref name=cmu>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmu.edu/commencement/event/main-ceremony/keynote.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513194526/http://www.cmu.edu/commencement/event/main-ceremony/keynote.html|url-status=dead|title=Speakers & Honorees-Commencement Weekend - Carnegie Mellon University<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref name=brhp/>{{rp|343}} He also worked as a rafting guide during the summer.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|42}}\n\nRalston worked as a mechanical engineer with [[Intel]] in [[Ocotillo, Arizona|Ocotillo]], [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]] and [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]] for five years, but found himself burned out by working in a large corporation. During his time as an engineer he had built up skills in mountaineering, and in 2002 he quit in order to climb [[Denali]]. He moved to [[Aspen, Colorado]] in order to pursue a life of climbing mountains.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|72}}\n\nRalston began working towards his goal of climbing all of Colorado's \"[[fourteener]]s\" \u2014 peaks over {{convert|14000|ft|m|round=10}} altitude, of which there are 59 \u2014 solo and during winter (a feat that had never been recorded before). In 2003, he was caught in a Grade 5 [[avalanche]] on Resolution Peak, Colorado with his [[skiing]] partners Mark Beverly and Chadwick Spencer. No one was seriously injured, but his friends did not speak to him in the aftermath, causing him to reevaluate his approach to risk management.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|141}}\n\n==Canyoneering accident==\nOn April 26, 2003, Aron Ralston was canyoneering alone through [[Bluejohn Canyon]], in eastern [[Wayne County, Utah|Wayne County]], [[Utah]], just south of the [[Horseshoe Canyon (Utah)|Horseshoe Canyon]] unit of [[Canyonlands National Park]]. While he was descending the lower stretches of the [[slot canyon]], a suspended boulder became dislodged while he was climbing down from it. The rock smashed his right hand, and then crushed his right hand against the canyon wall.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedailymirror/2010/11/aron-ralston-the-real-story.html | website=Los Angeles Times | title=Aron Ralston \u2013 the Real Story |publisher=The Times |date=May 3, 2003 |author1=Stephanie Simon |author2=J. Michael Kennedy}}</ref> Ralston had not informed anyone of his hiking plans, nor did he have any way to call for help. \n\nAssuming that he would die without intervention, he spent five days slowly sipping his small amount of remaining water, approximately 350 ml (12 imp fl oz), and slowly eating his small amount of food, two [[burritos]], while repeatedly trying to extricate his arm. His efforts were futile as he was unable to free his arm from the 800&nbsp;lb (360&nbsp;kg) chockstone. After three days of trying to lift and break the boulder, the [[dehydrated]] and [[Delirium|delirious]] Ralston prepared to [[amputate]] his trapped arm at a point on the mid-[[forearm]] in order to escape. After having experimented with [[tourniquet]]s and having made exploratory superficial cuts to his forearm, he realized, on the fourth day, that in order to free his arm he would have to cut through the bones in it, but the tools available were insufficient to do so.<ref name=brhp/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1821786/aron-ralston-between-rock-and-hardest-place|title=Aron Ralston - Between a Rock and the Hardest Place|first=Mark|last=Jenkins|date=August 1, 2003|website=Outside Online}}</ref>\n\nAfter running out of food and water on the fifth day, Ralston decided to [[Urophagia|drink his own urine]]. He carved his name, date of birth and presumed date of death into the sandstone canyon wall, and videotaped his last goodbyes to his family. He did not expect to survive the night, but as he attempted to stay warm he began hallucinating and had a vision of himself playing with a future child while missing part of his right arm. Ralston credited this as giving him the belief that he would live.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|248}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/news/hiker-who-cut-arm-my-future-son-saved-me-wbna34325633|title=Hiker who cut off arm: My future son saved me|author=Michael Inbar|date=December 9, 2009|website=TODAY.com}}</ref> \n\nAfter waking at dawn the following day he discovered that his arm had begun to [[decompose]] due to the lack of circulation, and became desperate to tear it off.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|279}} Ralston then had an [[epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]] that he could break his [[Radius (bone)|radius]] and [[ulna]] bones using [[torque]] against his trapped arm. He did so, then amputated his forearm with his [[multi-tool]], using the dull two-inch knife and pliers for the tougher tendons. The process took an hour, during which time he used tubing from a CamelBak as a tourniquet, taking care to leave major arteries until last. The manufacturer of the multi-tool was never named, but Ralston said \"it was not a [[Leatherman]] but what you'd get if you bought a $15 flashlight and got a free [[Multi-tool|multi-use tool]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/nation/20030509climbernat2.asp|title=CMU grad describes cutting off his arm to save his life|accessdate=2007-03-21 | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | first=J. Michael | last=Kennedy | date=May 9, 2003| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070428163606/http://www.post-gazette.com/nation/20030509climbernat2.asp| archivedate= 28 April 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=brhp/>\n\nAfter freeing himself, Ralston climbed out of the slot canyon in which he had been trapped, [[rappell]]ed down a {{convert|65|ft|m|sp=us|adj=on}} sheer wall, then hiked out of the canyon, all one-handed. He was {{convert|8|mi|km}} from his vehicle, and had no phone. However, after {{convert|6|mi|km}} of hiking, he encountered a family on vacation from the [[Netherlands]]; Eric and Monique Meijer and their son Andy, who gave him food and water and hurried to alert the authorities. Ralston had feared he would bleed to death; he had lost {{convert|40|lbs|kg|adj=off}}, including 25% of his blood volume.<ref name=gq>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/aron-ralston-survivor-of-the-year-boulder-arm|title=Profile of Aron Ralston, GQ's 2003 Survivor of the Year|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=GQ}}</ref> Rescuers searching for Ralston, alerted by his family that he was missing, had narrowed the search down to Canyonlands and he was picked up by a helicopter in a wide area of the canyon. He was rescued approximately four hours after amputating his arm.<ref name=brhp/>\n\nRalston later said that if he had amputated his arm earlier, he would have bled to death before being found, while if he had not done it he would have been found dead in the slot canyon days later.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nHis severed hand and forearm were retrieved from under the boulder by park authorities. According to television presenter [[Tom Brokaw]],<ref name=\"Desperate days in Blue John Canyon\">{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLB3663D1A77433C3F|series=Dateline NBC|network=NBC|date =September 10, 2004|transcript=Dateline NBC|transcript-url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/5956900/ns/dateline_nbc/t/desperate-days-blue-john-canyon/|title=Desperate days in Blue John Canyon|work=Dateline NBC|author=Tom Brokaw |author2=Colleen Halpin}}</ref> it took 13 men, a [[winch]] and a [[hydraulic jack]] to move the boulder so that Ralston's arm could be removed. His arm was then [[Cremation|cremated]] and the ashes given to Ralston. He returned to the accident scene with Tom Brokaw and a camera crew six months later, on his 28th birthday, to film a ''[[Dateline NBC]]'' special about the accident in which he scattered the ashes of his arm there, where, he said, they belong.\n\n==After the accident==\n\n[[File:Aron Ralston on Independence Pass.jpg|thumb|Ralston in the mountains of central Colorado, near Independence Pass, [[Aspen, Colorado|Aspen]], in 2009|300x300px]]\nAfter the accident occurred, Ralston made numerous appearances in the media.<ref name=profile/> On July 21, 2003, Ralston appeared on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', and his story was featured by ''GQ's'' \"Men of the Year\u201d and ''Vanity Fair's'' \"People of 2003\".<ref name=gq/><ref name=brhp/>{{rp|340}}\n\nRalston documented his experience in an autobiographical book titled ''[[Between a Rock and a Hard Place (book)|Between a Rock and a Hard Place]],'' published by Atria Books in September, 2004. It reached #3 on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Hardcover Non-Fiction list]]. It hit #1 in New Zealand and Australia, and is the #7 best-selling [[memoir]] of all-time in the United Kingdom.<ref name=profile/> Later that month, Ralston's story was featured on a two-hour edition of ''[[Dateline NBC]]'' called \"Desperate Days in Blue John Canyon\".<ref name=\"Desperate days in Blue John Canyon\"/> Ralston has appeared twice on ''[[The Today Show]],'' ''[[Good Morning America]],'' and ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]].''<ref name=profile/> He has also appeared on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]],'' ''[[American Morning|CNN's American Morning with Bill Hemmer]],'' ''[[Minute to Win It]],'' ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]],'' ''[[CNN#Saturday|CNN Saturday Morning]],''  ''[[Enough Rope]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/netw/200410/highlights/242129.htm |publisher=ABC Australia |title=Enough Rope with Andrew Denton}}</ref> and ''[[CBS Evening News|CNBC with Deborah Norville]].''<ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=http://keynotespeakers.com/speaker_detail.php?speakerid=5177 |title=Aron Ralston - Speaker Profile |publisher=Keynotespeakers.com |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref> On September 28, 2004, he appeared on the radio program [[The Bob Rivers Show]] and described his ordeal as \"six days of terror and horror.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bobrivers.com/index.php/aron-ralston-cut-off-own-arm-to-save-his-life/ |author= Ralston, Aron |date= September 28, 2004 |title= Aron Ralston, cut off own arm to save his life |publisher= The Bob Rivers Show |accessdate= May 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter his recovery he continued to climb mountains, including [[Aconcagua]] in 2005<ref name=tan>http://edition.cnn.com/2005/US/04/04/cnn25.tan.ralston/index.html</ref>, and in 2008, [[Ojos del Salado]] in [[Chile]] and [[Monte Pissis]] in [[Argentina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/article/889506--between-a-rock-and-a-happy-place |title=Between a rock and a happy place |accessdate=2010-12-12 | location=Toronto |work=[[Toronto Star|The Star]] |first=Peter |last=Howell |date=2010-11-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101115050905/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/article/889506--between-a-rock-and-a-happy-place| archivedate= 15 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 2005, Ralston became the first person to climb all 59 ranked and/or named [[List of Colorado fourteeners|Colorado's 'fourteeners']] solo in winter, a project he started in 1997 and resumed after the amputation in Bluejohn Canyon.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://outsideonline.com/outside/features/200604/aron-ralston-1.html |title=My Summit Problem |accessdate=2007-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100902013448/http://outsideonline.com/outside/features/200604/aron-ralston-1.html |author=Aron Ralston |date=August 2006|publisher=Outisde Magazine|archivedate=2010-09-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.14ers.com/|title=14ers.com|accessdate=2010-11-07| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101119071925/http://14ers.com/|publisher=14ers Inc| archivedate= 19 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mutrie|first=Tim|title=Ralston sends it: First solo winter fourteener project complete|url=http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20050311/NEWS/103110014|work=[[The Aspen Times]]|date=2005-03-11|accessdate=2011-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707175755/http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20050311/NEWS/103110014|archive-date=2011-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Ralston was featured as a panelist in Miller Lite's \"[[Man Laws]]\" ad campaign.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disaboom.com/athletes-with-disabilities/catching-up-with-aron-ralston |title=Catching Up with Aron Ralston |publisher=Disaboom.com |accessdate=2010-10-19| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101007210722/http://www.disaboom.com/athletes-with-disabilities/catching-up-with-aron-ralston| archivedate= 7 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.assurantemployeebenefits.com/shiningstar/2003Ralston.html |title=Perseverance Hall of Fame |publisher=Assurantemployeebenefits.com |accessdate=2010-10-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224235341/http://www.assurantemployeebenefits.com/shiningstar/2003Ralston.html |archivedate=2010-12-24 }}</ref> \n\nHe later noted that surviving being trapped in the canyon had given him a sense of invincibility, at a time that it should have humbled him. He lost friends to suicide, and became depressed after his girlfriend broke up with him in 2006, and has tried to shift his focus away from adventure seeking for esteem purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/127-hours-aron-ralstons-story-survival/|title=127 Hours: Aron Ralston's story of survival|first=Alex|last=Hannaford|date=March 15, 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/31/sports/othersports/01ralston.html|title=Climber Still Seeks Larger Meaning in His Epic Escape|first=Michael|last=Brick|date=March 31, 2009|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> \n\nIn 2008, Ralston signed on to advise polar explorer [[Eric Larsen (explorer)|Eric Larsen]] on his 2009/2010 \"Save the Poles\" expedition, of traveling to the north and south poles, and climbing Mount Everest (sometimes referred to as the third pole) within the same year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/39084364/ns/us_news-environment/t/record-set-trekker-does-everest-both-poles-year/|title=Record set: Trekker does Everest, both poles in a year|date=October 15, 2010|website=msnbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/27841486|title=Explorers eye poles, Everest on climate mission|publisher=[[NBC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 21, 2008|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Aspen Times|url=https://www.aspentimes.com/news/explorer-takes-on-poles-everest/|title=Explorer takes on Poles, Everest|author=Pat Graham|date=November 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705296046/Ralston-says-accident-was-a-blessing-in-a-way.html|title=Ralston says accident was 'a blessing in a way'|date=April 9, 2009|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009, Ralston married Jessica Trusty. Their first child was born in February 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Inbar |first=Michael |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/34325633/ns/today-today_people/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212232918/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/34325633/ns/today-today_people |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-12-12 |title=Hiker who cut off arm: My future son saved me - TODAY People - People: Tales of survival |publisher=Today.msnbc.msn.com |date=2009-12-08 |accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pickmeupmagazine.co.uk/real_lives/Pick_Me_Up_CATCHUP_article_292602.html |title=Pick Me Up CATCH-UP |publisher=Pick Me Up magazine |accessdate=2010-10-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901074127/http://www.pickmeupmagazine.co.uk/real_lives/Pick_Me_Up_CATCHUP_article_292602.html |archivedate=September 1, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flicksandbits.com/2010/10/08/aron-ralston-interview-the-man-whos-real-life-story-danny-boyles-upcoming-movie-127-hours-is-based-on/3988/ |title=Aron Ralston Interview \u2013 The Man Who\u2019s (sic) Real Life Story Danny Boyle\u2019s upcoming Movie \u2019127 Hours\u2019 Is Based On |publisher=Flicks and Bits |date=2010-10-08 |accessdate=2010-10-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011114617/http://www.flicksandbits.com/2010/10/08/aron-ralston-interview-the-man-whos-real-life-story-danny-boyles-upcoming-movie-127-hours-is-based-on/3988/ |archivedate=11 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Ralston was a contestant on the U.S. television show ''[[Minute To Win It]],'' where he won $125,000 for Wilderness Workshop,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/one-armed-adventurer-to-take-part-in-game-show_1203020|title=James Franco - One-armed Adventurer To Take Part In Game Show - Contactmusic.com|author=WENN|work=Contactmusic.com}}</ref> made a cameo on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' in \"[[Treehouse of Horror XXII]]\".<ref>https://www.thewrap.com/simpson-treehouse-horror-al-jean-2012-halloween-dexter-ralston-farting-homer/</ref><ref>[http://www.mediamarketjournal.com/2011/10/fox-details-the-simpsons-oct-30-episode-treehouse-of-horror-xxii/ \"Fox Details \u2018The Simpsons,\u2019 Oct. 30 Episode: \u2018Treehouse of Horror XXII\u2019\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121072436/http://mediamarketjournal.com/2011/10/fox-details-the-simpsons-oct-30-episode-treehouse-of-horror-xxii/ |date=2018-11-21 }}. 2011-10-24. mediamarketjournal.com, Retrieved 2011-11-01</ref>, took part in the reality show ''[[Alone in the Wild]],'' where he had to 'survive' in the wild with a video camera and a bag of supplies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/tv/programs/alone-in-the-wild|title=Alone In The Wild|website=ABC Television}}</ref> and delivered the [[commencement speech]] on May 15, 2011, at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] for the graduating classes of 2011 and 2013.<ref name=cmu/>\n\nHe has also appeared on the [[Comedy Central]] show ''[[Tosh.0]]'' in a sketch with host [[Daniel Tosh]] and another climber in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tosh.comedycentral.com/video-clips/web-redemption---s--tty-rock-climber---uncensored|title=Web Redemption - S**tty Rock Climber - Uncensored|work=Tosh.0}}</ref>\n\n===Assault charge===\nIn 2013, Ralston and his girlfriend, Vita Shannon, who have a daughter together, were both arrested after an altercation at their home. The circumstances of the altercation are unclear. Charges against Ralston were dropped shortly after, and charges against Shannon were dropped after he did not show up to a court hearing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/12/09/denver-drops-aron-ralston-case-girlfriend-pleads-not-guilty/|title=Denver drops Aron Ralston case; girlfriend pleads not guilty|first=Tom McGhee &#124; Special to The Denver|last=Post|date=December 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/domestic-case-dropped-against-aron-ralston-who-cut-off-own-arm/|author2=P. SOLOMON BANDA|author1=DAN ELLIOTT|title=Domestic case dropped against Aron Ralston, who cut off own arm|date=9 December 2013|website=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kdvr.com/2014/02/21/vita-shannon-cleared-in-domestic-violence-charges-with-aron-ralston/|title=Vita Shannon cleared in domestic violence charges with Aron Ralston|date=February 22, 2014|author=Thomas Hendrick |publisher=[[KDVR]]}}</ref>\n\n===Public speaking===\nAs a corporate speaker, Ralston receives an [[honorarium]] of about $25,000 per domestic speaking appearance, and up to $37,000 for international speeches.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/31/sports/othersports/01ralston.html Pushing the Limit] NY Times, March 31, 2009</ref> On May 4, 2007, Ralston appeared at the Swiss Economic Forum and gave a speech about \"how he did not lose his hand, but gained his life back.\"\n\n[[File:Aron Ralston 127 Hours.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.90|Ralston at the Toronto premiere of ''[[127 Hours]]'']]\n\n==''127 Hours''==\n{{main|127 Hours}}\nBritish film director [[Danny Boyle]] directed the film ''[[127 Hours]]'' about Ralston's accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34398/spend-127-hours-with-danny-boyle |title=Spend 127 Hours with Danny Boyle |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref> Filming took place in March and April 2010, with a release in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]] on November 5, 2010. [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] funded the film.<ref>{{cite news|author=Xan Brooks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/nov/05/danny-boyle-aron-ralston |title=Danny Boyle climbs on mountaineer epic 127 Hours |newspaper=Guardian |date= 2009-11-05|accessdate=2010-10-19 |location=London}}</ref> Actor [[James Franco]] played the role of Ralston.<ref>{{cite news |title = James Franco puts in 'Hours' |first = Tatiana |last = Siegel |url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118013420.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher = [[Reed Business Information]] |date =  January 6, 2010 |accessdate = June 19, 2010 }}</ref> The movie received standing ovations at both the [[Telluride Film Festival]] and the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. Some of the audience members in Toronto fainted during the final amputation scene.<ref>{{cite news |title = Audience faints at 'realistic' amputation film |url = http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/audience-faints--at-realistic-amputation-film-20100915-15bpo.html?autostart=1 |date =  September 15, 2010 |accessdate = September 15, 2010 | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | first=Christine | last=Kellett| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100918220705/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/audience-faints--at-realistic-amputation-film-20100915-15bpo.html?autostart=1| archivedate= 18 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe film received widespread acclaim by critics and review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 93% of 226 professional critics have given the film a positive review, with an average rating of 8.3/10.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/127_hours/\n|title=128 Hours | work = Rotten Tomatoes | publisher = [[Flixster]] | accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[83rd Academy Awards]] in 2011 the film was nominated for six [[Academy Award|Oscars]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] (won by ''[[The King's Speech]]'') and [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Franco (won by [[Colin Firth]] for his role in ''The King's Speech''). ''127 Hours'' was also nominated in the categories for [[Academy Award for Best Writing (Adapted Screenplay)|Best Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]], and [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Editing]].\n\nOf the authenticity of ''127 Hours,'' Ralston has said that the film is \"so factually accurate it is as close to a documentary as you can get and still be a drama,\" and he jokingly added that he thought it is \"the best film ever made.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/dec/15/story-danny-boyles-127-hours | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Patrick | last=Barkham | title=The extraordinary story behind Danny Boyle's 127 Hours | date=2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Aron Ralston}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.aronralstonspeaker.com}}\n*[http://aronralstonadventure.com/ Adventure website]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101420504 Redux: A Climber's Survival Tale]\n*[http://www.wideworldmag.com/2010/11/09/127-hours-in-the-life-of-aron-ralston/ Aron Ralston: in his own words]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ralston, Aron}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American amputees]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:American mountain climbers]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Mellon University College of Engineering alumni]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Intel people]]\n[[Category:People from Aspen, Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Indianapolis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = \n| image = Aron Ralston on Capitol Peak Winter 2003.JPG\n| image_size = \n| alt = Aron Ralston standing in the snow on the top of Capitol Peak\n| caption = Ralston on Capitol Peak in winter 2003\n| birth_name = Aron Lee Ralston\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1975|10|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Marion, Ohio|Marion]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"birth\">Ohio Birth Index, 1908-2011</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Carnegie Mellon University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| occupation = [[Motivational speaker]], [[mountaineer]], [[mechanical engineer]]\n| notable_works = ''[[Between a Rock and a Hard Place (book)|Between a Rock and a Hard Place]]''\n| residence = \n| spouse = {{marriage|Jessica Trusty|2009|2012|end=divorced}}\n| partner= Vita Shannon (2012&ndash;2013)\n| children = 2|\n}}\n'''Aron Lee Ralston''' (born October 27, 1975) is an [[United States|American]] [[outdoorsman]], [[mechanical engineer]] and [[motivational speaker]] known for surviving a [[canyoneering]] accident by cutting off his own arm. During a solo descent of [[Bluejohn Canyon]] in southeastern [[Utah]] he dislodged a boulder, pinning his right wrist to the side of the canyon wall. After five days he was able to amputate his arm with a dull pocketknife, make his way through the rest of the canyon, rappel down a {{convert|65|feet|m|adj=on}} drop, and hike {{convert|7|miles|km}} to safety.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/may/03/duncancampbell |title=Mountaineer trapped by boulder amputated arm with pocketknife|newspaper=The Guardian |author=Duncan Campbell |date=2003-05-03 |accessdate=2010-12-13 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=brhp>{{cite book|author=Aron Ralston|title=Between a Rock and a Hard Place |url=https://archive.org/details/betweenrockandha00rals|url-access=registration|isbn=0-7432-6354-5|publisher=Atria Books|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nThe incident is documented in Ralston's autobiography ''[[Between a Rock and a Hard Place (book)|Between a Rock and a Hard Place]]'' and is the subject of the 2010 film ''[[127 Hours]]'' where he is portrayed by [[James Franco]].\n\nAfter the accident he continued mountaineering and became the first person to ascend all of [[List of Colorado fourteeners|Colorado's fourteeners]] solo in winter.\n\n==Early life==\n\nAron Ralston was born on October 27, 1975 in [[Marion, Ohio]].<ref name=\"birth\"/> He and his family moved to [[Denver]] when he was 12, where he attended Cherry Creek High School and learned to ski and backpack. He received his college degree from [[Carnegie Mellon University]] in [[Pittsburgh]], finishing with degrees in mechanical engineering and [[French language|French]], with a minor in [[piano]].<ref name=brhp/> At Carnegie Mellon, he served as a resident assistant, studied abroad, and was an active [[intramural sports]] participant.<ref name=cmu>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmu.edu/commencement/event/main-ceremony/keynote.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513194526/http://www.cmu.edu/commencement/event/main-ceremony/keynote.html|url-status=dead|title=Speakers & Honorees-Commencement Weekend - Carnegie Mellon University<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref name=brhp/>{{rp|343}} He also worked as a rafting guide during the summer.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|42}}\n\nRalston worked as a mechanical engineer with [[Intel]] in [[Ocotillo, Arizona|Ocotillo]], [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]] and [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]] for five years, but found himself burned out by working in a large corporation. During his time as an engineer he had built up skills in mountaineering, and in 2002 he quit in order to climb [[Denali]]. He moved to [[Aspen, Colorado]] in order to pursue a life of climbing mountains.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|72}}\n\nRalston began working towards his goal of climbing all of Colorado's \"[[fourteener]]s\" \u2014 peaks over {{convert|14000|ft|m|round=10}} altitude, of which there are 59 \u2014 solo and during winter (a feat that had never been recorded before). In 2003, he was caught in a Grade 5 [[avalanche]] on Resolution Peak, Colorado with his [[skiing]] partners Mark Beverly and Chadwick Spencer. No one was seriously injured, but his friends did not speak to him in the aftermath, causing him to reevaluate his approach to risk management.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|141}}\n\n==Canyoneering accident==\nOn April 26, 2003, Aron Ralston was canyoneering alone through [[Bluejohn Canyon]], in eastern [[Wayne County, Utah|Wayne County]], [[Utah]], just south of the [[Horseshoe Canyon (Utah)|Horseshoe Canyon]] unit of [[Canyonlands National Park]]. While he was descending the lower stretches of the [[slot canyon]], a suspended boulder became dislodged while he was climbing down from it. The rock smashed his right hand, and then crushed his right hand against the canyon wall.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedailymirror/2010/11/aron-ralston-the-real-story.html | website=Los Angeles Times | title=Aron Ralston \u2013 the Real Story |publisher=The Times |date=May 3, 2003 |author1=Stephanie Simon |author2=J. Michael Kennedy}}</ref> Ralston had not informed anyone of his hiking plans, nor did he have any way to call for help. \n\nAssuming that he would die without intervention, he spent five days slowly sipping his small amount of remaining water, approximately 350 ml (12 imp fl oz), and slowly eating his small amount of food, two [[burritos]], while repeatedly trying to extricate his arm. His efforts were futile as he was unable to free his arm from the 800&nbsp;lb (360&nbsp;kg) chockstone. After three days of trying to lift and break the boulder, the [[dehydrated]] and [[Delirium|delirious]] Ralston prepared to [[amputate]] his trapped arm at a point on the mid-[[forearm]] in order to escape. After having experimented with [[tourniquet]]s and having made exploratory superficial cuts to his forearm, he realized, on the fourth day, that in order to free his arm he would have to cut through the bones in it, but the tools available were insufficient to do so.<ref name=brhp/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1821786/aron-ralston-between-rock-and-hardest-place|title=Aron Ralston - Between a Rock and the Hardest Place|first=Mark|last=Jenkins|date=August 1, 2003|website=Outside Online}}</ref>\n\nAfter running out of food and water on the fifth day, Ralston decided to [[Urophagia|drink his own urine]]. He carved his name, date of birth and presumed date of death into the sandstone canyon wall, and videotaped his last goodbyes to his family. He did not expect to survive the night, but as he attempted to stay warm he began hallucinating and had a vision of himself playing with a future child while missing part of his right arm. Ralston credited this as giving him the belief that he would live.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|248}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/news/hiker-who-cut-arm-my-future-son-saved-me-wbna34325633|title=Hiker who cut off arm: My future son saved me|author=Michael Inbar|date=December 9, 2009|website=TODAY.com}}</ref> \n\nAfter waking at dawn the following day he discovered that his arm had begun to [[decompose]] due to the lack of circulation, and became desperate to tear it off.<ref name=brhp/>{{rp|279}} Ralston then had an [[epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]] that he could break his [[Radius (bone)|radius]] and [[ulna]] bones using [[torque]] against his trapped arm. He did so, then amputated his forearm with his [[multi-tool]], using the dull two-inch knife and pliers for the tougher tendons. The process took an hour, during which time he used tubing from a CamelBak as a tourniquet, taking care to leave major arteries until last. The manufacturer of the multi-tool was never named, but Ralston said \"it was not a [[Leatherman]] but what you'd get if you bought a $15 flashlight and got a free [[Multi-tool|multi-use tool]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/nation/20030509climbernat2.asp|title=CMU grad describes cutting off his arm to save his life|accessdate=2007-03-21 | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | first=J. Michael | last=Kennedy | date=May 9, 2003| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070428163606/http://www.post-gazette.com/nation/20030509climbernat2.asp| archivedate= 28 April 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=brhp/>\n\nAfter freeing himself, Ralston climbed out of the slot canyon in which he had been trapped, [[rappell]]ed down a {{convert|65|ft|m|sp=us|adj=on}} sheer wall, then hiked out of the canyon, all one-handed. He was {{convert|8|mi|km}} from his vehicle, and had no phone. However, after {{convert|6|mi|km}} of hiking, he encountered a family on vacation from the [[Netherlands]]; Eric and Monique Meijer and their son Andy, who gave him food and water and hurried to alert the authorities. Ralston had feared he would bleed to death; he had lost {{convert|40|lbs|kg|adj=off}}, including 25% of his blood volume.<ref name=gq>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/aron-ralston-survivor-of-the-year-boulder-arm|title=Profile of Aron Ralston, GQ's 2003 Survivor of the Year|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=GQ}}</ref> Rescuers searching for Ralston, alerted by his family that he was missing, had narrowed the search down to Canyonlands and he was picked up by a helicopter in a wide area of the canyon. He was rescued approximately four hours after amputating his arm.<ref name=brhp/>\n\nRalston later said that if he had amputated his arm earlier, he would have bled to death before being found, while if he had not done it he would have been found dead in the slot canyon days later.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nHis severed hand and forearm were retrieved from under the boulder by park authorities. According to television presenter [[Tom Brokaw]],<ref name=\"Desperate days in Blue John Canyon\">{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLB3663D1A77433C3F|series=Dateline NBC|network=NBC|date =September 10, 2004|transcript=Dateline NBC|transcript-url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/5956900/ns/dateline_nbc/t/desperate-days-blue-john-canyon/|title=Desperate days in Blue John Canyon|work=Dateline NBC|author=Tom Brokaw |author2=Colleen Halpin}}</ref> it took 13 men, a [[winch]] and a [[hydraulic jack]] to move the boulder so that Ralston's arm could be removed. His arm was then [[Cremation|cremated]] and the ashes given to Ralston. He returned to the accident scene with Tom Brokaw and a camera crew six months later, on his 28th birthday, to film a ''[[Dateline NBC]]'' special about the accident in which he scattered the ashes of his arm there, where, he said, they belong.\n\n==After the accident==\n\n[[File:Aron Ralston on Independence Pass.jpg|thumb|Ralston in the mountains of central Colorado, near Independence Pass, [[Aspen, Colorado|Aspen]], in 2009|300x300px]]\nAfter the accident occurred, Ralston made numerous appearances in the media.<ref name=profile/> On July 21, 2003, Ralston appeared on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', and his story was featured by ''GQ's'' \"Men of the Year\u201d and ''Vanity Fair's'' \"People of 2003\".<ref name=gq/><ref name=brhp/>{{rp|340}}\n\nRalston documented his experience in an autobiographical book titled ''[[Between a Rock and a Hard Place (book)|Between a Rock and a Hard Place]],'' published by Atria Books in September, 2004. It reached #3 on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Hardcover Non-Fiction list]]. It hit #1 in New Zealand and Australia, and is the #7 best-selling [[memoir]] of all-time in the United Kingdom.<ref name=profile/> Later that month, Ralston's story was featured on a two-hour edition of ''[[Dateline NBC]]'' called \"Desperate Days in Blue John Canyon\".<ref name=\"Desperate days in Blue John Canyon\"/> Ralston has appeared twice on ''[[The Today Show]],'' ''[[Good Morning America]],'' and ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]].''<ref name=profile/> He has also appeared on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]],'' ''[[American Morning|CNN's American Morning with Bill Hemmer]],'' ''[[Minute to Win It]],'' ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]],'' ''[[CNN#Saturday|CNN Saturday Morning]],''  ''[[Enough Rope]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/netw/200410/highlights/242129.htm |publisher=ABC Australia |title=Enough Rope with Andrew Denton}}</ref> and ''[[CBS Evening News|CNBC with Deborah Norville]].''<ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=http://keynotespeakers.com/speaker_detail.php?speakerid=5177 |title=Aron Ralston - Speaker Profile |publisher=Keynotespeakers.com |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref> On September 28, 2004, he appeared on the radio program [[The Bob Rivers Show]] and described his ordeal as \"six days of terror and horror.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bobrivers.com/index.php/aron-ralston-cut-off-own-arm-to-save-his-life/ |author= Ralston, Aron |date= September 28, 2004 |title= Aron Ralston, cut off own arm to save his life |publisher= The Bob Rivers Show |accessdate= May 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter his recovery he continued to climb mountains, including [[Aconcagua]] in 2005<ref name=tan>http://edition.cnn.com/2005/US/04/04/cnn25.tan.ralston/index.html</ref>, and in 2008, [[Ojos del Salado]] in [[Chile]] and [[Monte Pissis]] in [[Argentina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/article/889506--between-a-rock-and-a-happy-place |title=Between a rock and a happy place |accessdate=2010-12-12 | location=Toronto |work=[[Toronto Star|The Star]] |first=Peter |last=Howell |date=2010-11-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101115050905/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/article/889506--between-a-rock-and-a-happy-place| archivedate= 15 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 2005, Ralston became the first person to climb all 59 ranked and/or named [[List of Colorado fourteeners|Colorado's 'fourteeners']] solo in winter, a project he started in 1997 and resumed after the amputation in Bluejohn Canyon.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://outsideonline.com/outside/features/200604/aron-ralston-1.html |title=My Summit Problem |accessdate=2007-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100902013448/http://outsideonline.com/outside/features/200604/aron-ralston-1.html |author=Aron Ralston |date=August 2006|publisher=Outisde Magazine|archivedate=2010-09-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.14ers.com/|title=14ers.com|accessdate=2010-11-07| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101119071925/http://14ers.com/|publisher=14ers Inc| archivedate= 19 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mutrie|first=Tim|title=Ralston sends it: First solo winter fourteener project complete|url=http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20050311/NEWS/103110014|work=[[The Aspen Times]]|date=2005-03-11|accessdate=2011-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707175755/http://www.aspentimes.com/article/20050311/NEWS/103110014|archive-date=2011-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Ralston was featured as a panelist in Miller Lite's \"[[Man Laws]]\" ad campaign.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disaboom.com/athletes-with-disabilities/catching-up-with-aron-ralston |title=Catching Up with Aron Ralston |publisher=Disaboom.com |accessdate=2010-10-19| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101007210722/http://www.disaboom.com/athletes-with-disabilities/catching-up-with-aron-ralston| archivedate= 7 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.assurantemployeebenefits.com/shiningstar/2003Ralston.html |title=Perseverance Hall of Fame |publisher=Assurantemployeebenefits.com |accessdate=2010-10-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224235341/http://www.assurantemployeebenefits.com/shiningstar/2003Ralston.html |archivedate=2010-12-24 }}</ref> \n\nHe later noted that surviving being trapped in the canyon had given him a sense of invincibility, at a time that it should have humbled him. He lost friends to suicide, and became depressed after his girlfriend broke up with him in 2006, and has tried to shift his focus away from adventure seeking for esteem purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/127-hours-aron-ralstons-story-survival/|title=127 Hours: Aron Ralston's story of survival|first=Alex|last=Hannaford|date=March 15, 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/31/sports/othersports/01ralston.html|title=Climber Still Seeks Larger Meaning in His Epic Escape|first=Michael|last=Brick|date=March 31, 2009|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> \n\nIn 2008, Ralston signed on to advise polar explorer [[Eric Larsen (explorer)|Eric Larsen]] on his 2009/2010 \"Save the Poles\" expedition, of traveling to the north and south poles, and climbing Mount Everest (sometimes referred to as the third pole) within the same year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/39084364/ns/us_news-environment/t/record-set-trekker-does-everest-both-poles-year/|title=Record set: Trekker does Everest, both poles in a year|date=October 15, 2010|website=msnbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/27841486|title=Explorers eye poles, Everest on climate mission|publisher=[[NBC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 21, 2008|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Aspen Times|url=https://www.aspentimes.com/news/explorer-takes-on-poles-everest/|title=Explorer takes on Poles, Everest|author=Pat Graham|date=November 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705296046/Ralston-says-accident-was-a-blessing-in-a-way.html|title=Ralston says accident was 'a blessing in a way'|date=April 9, 2009|website=DeseretNews.com}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009, Ralston married Jessica Trusty. Their first child was born in February 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Inbar |first=Michael |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/34325633/ns/today-today_people/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212232918/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/34325633/ns/today-today_people |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-12-12 |title=Hiker who cut off arm: My future son saved me - TODAY People - People: Tales of survival |publisher=Today.msnbc.msn.com |date=2009-12-08 |accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pickmeupmagazine.co.uk/real_lives/Pick_Me_Up_CATCHUP_article_292602.html |title=Pick Me Up CATCH-UP |publisher=Pick Me Up magazine |accessdate=2010-10-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901074127/http://www.pickmeupmagazine.co.uk/real_lives/Pick_Me_Up_CATCHUP_article_292602.html |archivedate=September 1, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flicksandbits.com/2010/10/08/aron-ralston-interview-the-man-whos-real-life-story-danny-boyles-upcoming-movie-127-hours-is-based-on/3988/ |title=Aron Ralston Interview \u2013 The Man Who\u2019s (sic) Real Life Story Danny Boyle\u2019s upcoming Movie \u2019127 Hours\u2019 Is Based On |publisher=Flicks and Bits |date=2010-10-08 |accessdate=2010-10-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011114617/http://www.flicksandbits.com/2010/10/08/aron-ralston-interview-the-man-whos-real-life-story-danny-boyles-upcoming-movie-127-hours-is-based-on/3988/ |archivedate=11 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Ralston was a contestant on the U.S. television show ''[[Minute To Win It]],'' where he won $125,000 for Wilderness Workshop,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/one-armed-adventurer-to-take-part-in-game-show_1203020|title=James Franco - One-armed Adventurer To Take Part In Game Show - Contactmusic.com|author=WENN|work=Contactmusic.com}}</ref> made a cameo on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' in \"[[Treehouse of Horror XXII]]\".<ref>https://www.thewrap.com/simpson-treehouse-horror-al-jean-2012-halloween-dexter-ralston-farting-homer/</ref><ref>[http://www.mediamarketjournal.com/2011/10/fox-details-the-simpsons-oct-30-episode-treehouse-of-horror-xxii/ \"Fox Details \u2018The Simpsons,\u2019 Oct. 30 Episode: \u2018Treehouse of Horror XXII\u2019\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121072436/http://mediamarketjournal.com/2011/10/fox-details-the-simpsons-oct-30-episode-treehouse-of-horror-xxii/ |date=2018-11-21 }}. 2011-10-24. mediamarketjournal.com, Retrieved 2011-11-01</ref>, took part in the reality show ''[[Alone in the Wild]],'' where he had to 'survive' in the wild with a video camera and a bag of supplies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/tv/programs/alone-in-the-wild|title=Alone In The Wild|website=ABC Television}}</ref> and delivered the [[commencement speech]] on May 15, 2011, at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] for the graduating classes of 2011 and 2013.<ref name=cmu/>\n\nHe has also appeared on the [[Comedy Central]] show ''[[Tosh.0]]'' in a sketch with host [[Daniel Tosh]] and another climber in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tosh.comedycentral.com/video-clips/web-redemption---s--tty-rock-climber---uncensored|title=Web Redemption - S**tty Rock Climber - Uncensored|work=Tosh.0}}</ref>\n\n===Assault charge===\nIn 2013, Ralston and his girlfriend, Vita Shannon, who have a daughter together, were both arrested after an altercation at their home. The circumstances of the altercation are unclear. Charges against Ralston were dropped shortly after, and charges against Shannon were dropped after he did not show up to a court hearing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/12/09/denver-drops-aron-ralston-case-girlfriend-pleads-not-guilty/|title=Denver drops Aron Ralston case; girlfriend pleads not guilty|first=Tom McGhee &#124; Special to The Denver|last=Post|date=December 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/domestic-case-dropped-against-aron-ralston-who-cut-off-own-arm/|author2=P. SOLOMON BANDA|author1=DAN ELLIOTT|title=Domestic case dropped against Aron Ralston, who cut off own arm|date=9 December 2013|website=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kdvr.com/2014/02/21/vita-shannon-cleared-in-domestic-violence-charges-with-aron-ralston/|title=Vita Shannon cleared in domestic violence charges with Aron Ralston|date=February 22, 2014|author=Thomas Hendrick |publisher=[[KDVR]]}}</ref>\n\n===Public speaking===\nAs a corporate speaker, Ralston receives an [[honorarium]] of about $25,000 per domestic speaking appearance, and up to $37,000 for international speeches.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/31/sports/othersports/01ralston.html Pushing the Limit] NY Times, March 31, 2009</ref> On May 4, 2007, Ralston appeared at the Swiss Economic Forum and gave a speech about \"how he did not lose his hand, but gained his life back.\"\n\n[[File:Aron Ralston 127 Hours.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.90|Ralston at the Toronto premiere of ''[[127 Hours]]'']]\n\n==''127 Hours''==\n{{main|127 Hours}}\nBritish film director [[Danny Boyle]] directed the film ''[[127 Hours]]'' about Ralston's accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34398/spend-127-hours-with-danny-boyle |title=Spend 127 Hours with Danny Boyle |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-19}}</ref> Filming took place in March and April 2010, with a release in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]] on November 5, 2010. [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] funded the film.<ref>{{cite news|author=Xan Brooks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/nov/05/danny-boyle-aron-ralston |title=Danny Boyle climbs on mountaineer epic 127 Hours |newspaper=Guardian |date= 2009-11-05|accessdate=2010-10-19 |location=London}}</ref> Actor [[James Franco]] played the role of Ralston.<ref>{{cite news |title = James Franco puts in 'Hours' |first = Tatiana |last = Siegel |url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118013420.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher = [[Reed Business Information]] |date =  January 6, 2010 |accessdate = June 19, 2010 }}</ref> The movie received standing ovations at both the [[Telluride Film Festival]] and the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. Some of the audience members in Toronto fainted during the final amputation scene.<ref>{{cite news |title = Audience faints at 'realistic' amputation film |url = http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/audience-faints--at-realistic-amputation-film-20100915-15bpo.html?autostart=1 |date =  September 15, 2010 |accessdate = September 15, 2010 | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | first=Christine | last=Kellett| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100918220705/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/audience-faints--at-realistic-amputation-film-20100915-15bpo.html?autostart=1| archivedate= 18 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe film received widespread acclaim by critics and review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 93% of 226 professional critics have given the film a positive review, with an average rating of 8.3/10.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">\n{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/127_hours/\n|title=128 Hours | work = Rotten Tomatoes | publisher = [[Flixster]] | accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[83rd Academy Awards]] in 2011 the film was nominated for six [[Academy Award|Oscars]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] (won by ''[[The King's Speech]]'') and [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Franco (won by [[Colin Firth]] for his role in ''The King's Speech''). ''127 Hours'' was also nominated in the categories for [[Academy Award for Best Writing (Adapted Screenplay)|Best Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]], and [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Editing]].\n\nOf the authenticity of ''127 Hours,'' Ralston has said that the film is \"so factually accurate it is as close to a documentary as you can get and still be a drama,\" and he jokingly added that he thought it is \"the best film ever made.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/dec/15/story-danny-boyles-127-hours | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Patrick | last=Barkham | title=The extraordinary story behind Danny Boyle's 127 Hours | date=2010-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Aron Ralston}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.aronralstonspeaker.com}}\n*[http://aronralstonadventure.com/ Adventure website]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101420504 Redux: A Climber's Survival Tale]\n*[http://www.wideworldmag.com/2010/11/09/127-hours-in-the-life-of-aron-ralston/ Aron Ralston: in his own words]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ralston, Aron}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American amputees]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:American mountain climbers]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Mellon University College of Engineering alumni]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Intel people]]\n[[Category:People from Aspen, Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Indianapolis]]\n", "name_user": "142.161.125.244", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aron_Ralston"}
